## Muslim-majority countries, states, districts, or towns

The terms "[Islamic world](/Islamic_world)" and "[Muslim world](/Muslim_world)" are often thrown around with a casual disregard for nuance, typically referring to the vast [Islamic](/Islamic) community, often known as the [Ummah](/Ummah). This collective theoretically encompasses all individuals who subscribe to the religious tenets, [politics](/Islamic_politics), and legal framework of [Islam](/Islam), or simply reside within societies where Islam is a dominant force. In a more contemporary, [geopolitical](/Geopolitics) context, these labels are generally applied to [countries where Islam is widespread](/Islam_by_country). However, the precise criteria for inclusion remain stubbornly undefined, leading to a perpetual state of ambiguity. Perhaps it's just easier to say "Muslim-majority countries," which, to no one's surprise, is the preferred alternative for those seeking a modicum of clarity.

The convoluted [history of the Muslim world](/History_of_Islam) stretches back approximately 1,400 years, a period punctuated by a bewildering array of socio-political evolutions, alongside undeniable leaps in the [arts](/Islamic_art), [science](/Science_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world), [medicine](/Medicine_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world), [philosophy](/Islamic_philosophy), [law](/Sharia), [economics](/Islamic_economics), and [technology](/List_of_inventions_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world) that collectively defined the so-called [Islamic Golden Age](/Islamic_Golden_Age). [Muslims](/Muslims) historically seek direction from the [Quran](/Quran) and uphold the [prophetic mission](/Prophets_and_messengers_in_Islam) of the [Islamic prophet](/Islamic_prophet) [Muhammad](/Muhammad). Yet, despite this shared foundation, disagreements on countless other matters have inevitably spawned a diverse landscape of religious [schools of thought](/Islamic_schools_and_branches) and [sects](/Sects_of_Islam) within Islam. The initial [Islamic conquests](/Early_Muslim_conquests), which saw the [Caliphate](/Caliphate) extend its reach across three continents—[Asia](/Asia), [Africa](/Africa), and [Europe](/Europe)—undoubtedly laid the economic groundwork for the flourishing of these institutions, a testament to the inherent emphasis placed on Islamic teachings. Fast forward to the modern era, and a significant portion of the Muslim world found itself under the heavy hand of European [colonial domination](/Colonialism). The subsequent emergence of independent nation-states in the post-colonial period has resulted in a fascinating, if chaotic, tapestry of political and economic models, all grappling with the enduring tension between secular and religious influences. It seems humanity can't quite make up its mind.

As of 2013, the combined [GDP (nominal)](/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)) of 50 Muslim-majority nations amounted to a respectable US$5.7 trillion. By 2016, this figure represented a modest 8% of the world's total economic output. However, by 2020, the [Economy of the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation](/Economy_of_the_Organisation_of_Islamic_Cooperation) (OIC), encompassing 57 member states, boasted a combined GDP (PPP) of US$24 trillion, a figure roughly equivalent to 18% of the global GDP. Should one include the 5 OIC observer states, this figure rises to an impressive US$30 trillion, or about 22% of the world's GDP. It's worth noting, of course, that some OIC member countries – such as [Ivory Coast](/Ivory_Coast), [Guyana](/Guyana), [Gabon](/Gabon), [Mozambique](/Mozambique), [Nigeria](/Nigeria), [Suriname](/Suriname), [Togo](/Togo), and [Uganda](/Uganda) – do not, in fact, maintain a Muslim majority within their populations. A minor detail, perhaps, but one that complicates any neat categorization.

In 2020, a staggering 1.8 billion individuals, representing over 25% of the global population, identified as [Muslims](/Muslims). Geographically, this demographic is concentrated, with 91% residing in the [Middle East](/Religion_in_the_Middle_East) and [North Africa](/Islam_in_Africa) ([MENA](/MENA)) region, 89% in [Central Asia](/Islam_in_Central_Asia), 40% in [Southeast Asia](/Islam_in_Southeast_Asia), 31% in [South Asia](/Islam_in_South_Asia), and 30% in [Sub-Saharan Africa](/Sub-Saharan_Africa). Looking at the broader continental picture, 25% of all Asians are Muslim, while only 1.4% of [Oceania](/Islam_in_Oceania)'s population, 6% of [Europe](/Islam_in_Europe)'s, and a mere 1% of [the Americas](/Islam_in_the_Americas)' population identify as such.

The vast majority of Muslims belong to one of two primary [denominations](/Islamic_schools_and_branches): [Sunni Islam](/Sunni_Islam) (comprising a dominant 87–90%) and [Shia Islam](/Shia_Islam) (making up the remaining 10–13%). However, the landscape is not entirely binary; other denominations persist in smaller pockets, such as [Ibadi Islam](/Ibadism), primarily concentrated in [Oman](/Oman). Those Muslims who do not affiliate with, self-identify with, or can't be neatly categorized under one of the established [Islamic schools and branches](/Islamic_schools_and_branches) are often referred to as [non-denominational Muslims](/Non-denominational_Muslims). A significant 13% of Muslims reside in [Indonesia](/Islam_in_Indonesia), which holds the title of the largest Muslim-majority country. However, [South Asia](/Islam_in_South_Asia) is home to the largest *total* population of Muslims globally, accounting for 31% of the world's Muslim faithful. The [Middle East–North Africa](/Middle_East_and_North_Africa) region, where Islam is the unequivocally dominant religion, hosts 20% of the global Muslim population, while 15% are found in [Sub-Saharan Africa](/Sub-Saharan_Africa) and [West Africa](/West_Africa), with a notable concentration in [Nigeria](/Islam_in_Nigeria). Muslims constitute an overwhelming majority in [Central Asia](/Islam_in_Central_Asia), comprise roughly half of the [Caucasus](/Caucasus)'s population, and are widely distributed throughout [Southeast Asia](/Islam_in_Southeast_Asia). [India](/Islam_in_India), remarkably, boasts the largest Muslim population outside of any Muslim-majority country. [Pakistan](/Islam_in_Pakistan), [Bangladesh](/Islam_in_Bangladesh), [Iran](/Islam_in_Iran), and [Egypt](/Islam_in_Egypt) follow, holding the world’s second, fourth, sixth, and seventh largest Muslim populations, respectively. Substantial [Muslim communities](/Islam_by_country) are also present in [the Americas](/Islam_in_the_Americas), [Russia](/Islam_in_Russia), [India](/Islam_in_India), [China](/Islam_in_China), and [Europe](/Islam_in_Europe). Islam is currently recognized as the [fastest-growing major religion globally](/Growth_of_religion), a phenomenon partly attributable to its comparatively high birth rate. Curiously, studies suggest that [religious switching](/Religious_conversion) has a negligible impact on the overall Muslim population, as the number of individuals who [embrace Islam](/Convert_to_Islam) and those who [leave Islam](/Apostasy_in_Islam) tend to be roughly balanced. China, despite its often-strained relationship with religious minorities, possesses the third-largest Muslim population outside of Muslim-majority states, while Russia holds the fifth-largest. Within Africa, Nigeria claims the largest Muslim population, and Indonesia, as previously noted, leads Asia in this regard.

## Terminology

The term "Islamic world" has a documented history stretching back to at least 1912, when it was used to encapsulate the perceived influence of [Pan-Islamist](/Pan-Islamism) [propaganda](/Propaganda). *[The Times](/The_Times)*, in a rather dramatic assessment, described [Pan-Islamism](/Pan-Islamism) as a movement imbued with power, importance, and a surprising cohesion, ostensibly born in Paris where a cosmopolitan mix of Turks, Arabs, and Persians converged. The correspondent's primary focus, however, was on India, bemoaning that it would "take too long to consider the progress made in various parts of the Muslim world." The article then proceeded to scrutinize the position of the Amir, the ripples caused by the [Tripoli Campaign](/Italo-Turkish_War), [Anglo-Russian](/Anglo-Russian) diplomatic maneuvers in Persia, and the ever-present "Afghan Ambitions." A truly global affair, it seems.

In its modern [geopolitical](/Geopolitics) iteration, the terms 'Muslim world' and 'Islamic world' are generally applied to [countries where Islam is widespread](/Islam_by_country). However, the precise criteria for their application remain frustratingly undefined. Some scholars and commentators, with a commendable commitment to complexity, have rightly criticized the simplistic, almost "binary" nature of labels like 'Muslim/Islamic world' and their derivatives, 'Muslim/Islamic country'. After all, no state is a religiously homogeneous monolith (consider [Egypt](/Egypt), where approximately 10% of its citizens are Christians). Furthermore, in sheer absolute numbers, it's not uncommon to find fewer Muslims residing in countries where they constitute a majority than in nations where they form a substantial minority. Moreover, the very notion of a uniform "Muslim world" is, to put it mildly, largely imagined. This concept, which gained traction in popular discourse during the nineteenth century, was initially weaponized by imperialists to underscore perceived civilizational disparities between the "East" and "West." Ironically, in a defiant counter-response to colonization, some Muslims later adopted the term themselves, attempting to forge a unified front against Western imperialism. Given these layers of historical baggage and inherent oversimplification, the term '[Muslim-majority countries](/List_of_Muslim-majority_countries)' is often seen as a more accurate, if less evocative, descriptor in academic literature.

## History

For a chronological guide, see [Timeline of the history of Islam](/Timeline_of_the_history_of_Islam).
See also: [History of the Middle East](/History_of_the_Middle_East)

