The [Tabula Rogeriana](/Tabula_Rogeriana), drawn by [Al-Idrisi](/Al-Idrisi) of [Sicily](/Sicily) in 1154, one of the most advanced [ancient world maps](/Ancient_world_maps). Al-Idrisi also wrote about the diverse Muslim communities found in various lands. Note: the map is here shown upside-down from the original to match current North/Up, South/Down map design

The [history of the Islamic faith](/History_of_Islam), both as a spiritual conviction and a burgeoning social institution, begins its intricate tapestry around 610 [CE](/Common_Era). It was then that the [Islamic prophet](/Prophets_of_Islam) [Muhammad](/Muhammad), a native of [Mecca](/Mecca), is believed by adherents to have received [the first revelation](/Muhammad%27s_first_revelation) of the [Quran](/Quran), initiating his mission to preach this new message. Facing considerable opposition within Mecca, he and his nascent community of followers undertook a pivotal migration in 622 CE to Yathrib, a settlement later known as [Medina](/Medina). Here, Muhammad was invited to establish a [new constitution](/Constitution_of_Medina) for the city, effectively assuming its leadership. This momentous migration, forever etched into history as the [Hijra](/Hegira), marks the inaugural year of the [Islamic calendar](/Islamic_calendar). By the time of his passing, Muhammad had solidified his position as the preeminent political and spiritual authority not only in Medina and Mecca but also across the surrounding region and among numerous other [tribes of Arabia](/Tribes_of_Arabia).

Following Muhammad's death in 632, his chosen successors, known as the [Caliphs](/Caliphs), continued to guide the Muslim community, drawing sustenance from his teachings and the divine directives of the [Quran](/Quran). The majority of Muslims reverently consider the initial four successors – [Abu Bakr](/Abu_Bakr), [Umar](/Umar), [Uthman](/Uthman), and [Ali](/Ali) – to be 'rightly guided', hence their collective designation as the [Rashidun](/Rashidun). The swift and expansive [conquests](/Early_Muslim_conquests) orchestrated by the [Rashidun Caliphate](/Rashidun_Caliphate) were instrumental in propelling the [spread of Islam](/Spread_of_Islam) far beyond the confines of the [Arabian Peninsula](/Arabian_Peninsula). This burgeoning empire stretched from the northwestern reaches of India, swept across [Central Asia](/Central_Asia), enveloped the [Near East](/Near_East), consumed [North Africa](/North_Africa), touched southern Italy, and eventually extended its dominion over the [Iberian Peninsula](/Iberian_Peninsula), reaching as far as the [Pyrenees](/Pyrenees). However, the Arab Muslims encountered an insurmountable obstacle in their attempts to fully subjugate the formidable Christian [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) in [Asia Minor](/Asia_Minor) during the protracted [Arab–Byzantine wars](/Arab%E2%80%93Byzantine_wars). The subsequent [Umayyad Caliphate](/Umayyad_Caliphate) made two determined, yet ultimately failed, attempts to besiege [Constantinople](/Constantinople) in [674–678](/Siege_of_Constantinople_(674%E2%80%93678)) and [717–718](/Siege_of_Constantinople_(717%E2%80%93718)). Meanwhile, the internal cohesion of the Muslim community itself began to fray, tearing itself apart into the rival [Sunni](/Sunni_Islam) and [Shia sects](/Shia_Islam) following the politically charged [killing of caliph Uthman](/Siege_of_Uthman) in 656. This tragic event ignited a bitter [succession crisis](/Succession_to_Muhammad), a schism that, to this day, remains unresolved. The ensuing periods of internal strife, famously known as the [First](/First_Fitna), [Second](/Second_Fitna), and [Third Fitnas](/Third_Fitna), culminating in the [Abbasid Revolution](/Abbasid_Revolution) (746–750), irrevocably shattered the political unity of the Muslims, leading to the proliferation of multiple, often competing, states that would define their geopolitical landscape for centuries to come.

The [Ghaznavids](/Ghaznavids)' rule in the Indian subcontinent eventually gave way to the ascendancy of the [Ghurid Empire](/Ghurid_dynasty), under the leadership of [Muhammad of Ghor](/Muhammad_of_Ghor) and [Ghiyath al-Din Muhammad](/Ghiyath_al-Din_Muhammad). Their influence, notably through the campaigns led by [Muhammad Bakhtiyar Khalji](/Muhammad_Bakhtiyar_Khalji), extended into [Bengal](/Bengal), a region where South Asian [Islamic missionaries](/Islamic_missionary_activity) achieved unparalleled success in their efforts of [dawah](/Dawah) and conversion to [Islam](/Islam). This period saw a significant demographic shift in the region. In 1206, [Qutb ud-Din Aibak](/Qutb_ud-Din_Aibak) successfully conquered Delhi, marking the inception of the [Delhi Sultanate](/Delhi_Sultanate). This successive series of dynasties proved remarkably adept at synthesizing elements of Indian civilization with the broader commercial and cultural networks spanning Africa and Eurasia. Their reign ushered in a period of considerable demographic and economic growth across India, effectively deterred Mongol incursions into the fertile [Indo-Gangetic Plain](/Indo-Gangetic_Plain), and even saw the enthronement of one of the few female Muslim rulers, [Razia Sultana](/Razia_Sultana).

Throughout history, a succession of powerful empires, predominantly Muslim, left an indelible mark on the global stage. These included the [Abbasids](/Abbasids), [Fatimids](/Fatimids), [Almoravids](/Almoravids), the [Gao Empire](/Gao_Empire), the [Seljukids](/Seljukids), and the [Songhai Empire](/Songhai_Empire) (15th-16th centuries), which, as one of the [largest contiguous](/List_of_largest_empires) empires of its time, dominated the [Sahel](/Sahel), [West Africa](/West_Africa), southern [North Africa](/North_Africa), and western [Central Africa](/Central_Africa). This empire was particularly notable for its control over vital centers of Islamic knowledge such as [Timbuktu](/Timbuktu), [Djenne](/Djenne), [Oualata](/Oualata), and [Gao](/Gao). Further south, the [Ajuran Sultanate](/Ajuran_Sultanate), [Adal Sultanate](/Adal_Sultanate), and Warsangali in [Somalia](/Somalia) also rose to prominence. In the Indian subcontinent, the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) (encompassing present-day India, [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh), [Pakistan](/Pakistan), etc.) exerted immense influence. The [Safavids](/Safavid) held sway in [Persia](/Persia), while the [Ottomans](/Ottoman_empire) dominated [Anatolia](/Anatolia) and beyond. Other significant West African powers included the [Massina Empire](/Massina_Empire), the [Sokoto Caliphate](/Sokoto_Caliphate) in northern [Nigeria](/Nigeria), and the [Toucouleur Empire](/Toucouleur_Empire). These empires collectively represented some of the most influential and distinguished powers of their respective eras. The 19th-century wave of colonialism, followed by the 20th-century process of decolonization, ultimately reshaped the global map, giving rise to numerous independent Muslim-majority states. These new nations adopted wildly divergent approaches to the role of Islam within their governance, with attitudes ranging from fervent religious adherence to staunch secularism. This ongoing ideological negotiation revolved around the fundamental question of Islam's compatibility with other powerful concepts such as [secularism](/Islam_and_secularism), [nationalism](/Nationalism) (particularly [Arab nationalism](/Arab_nationalism) and [Pan-Arabism](/Pan-Arabism), often in opposition to [Pan-Islamism](/Pan-Islamism)), [socialism](/Islamic_socialism) (manifesting in forms like [Arab socialism](/Arab_socialism) and [socialism in Iran](/Socialism_in_Iran)), [democracy](/Islamic_democracy), [republicanism](/Republicanism) (leading to the creation of [Islamic republics](/Islamic_republic)), [liberalism and progressivism](/Liberalism_and_progressivism_within_Islam), [feminism](/Islamic_feminism), and [capitalism](/Capitalism_and_Islam), among others.

### Gunpowder empires

The term "[Age of the Islamic Gunpowders](/Age_of_the_Islamic_Gunpowders)" is frequently employed by scholars to delineate a specific, transformative period dominated by the [Safavid](/Safavid_Empire), [Ottoman](/Ottoman_Empire), and [Mughal](/Mughal_Empire) states. These three formidable empires shared a common, and indeed defining, characteristic: their exceptional military prowess, which was largely attributable to their innovative and effective utilization of newly developed [firearms](/Firearms). Specifically, the strategic deployment of advanced [cannon](/Cannon) and versatile small arms allowed them to establish and expand their vast dominions with unprecedented efficiency. This era of powerful, gunpowder-fueled empires primarily spanned from the fourteenth to the late seventeenth centuries, fundamentally altering the geopolitical landscape of their respective regions. During the 17th and 18th centuries, the [Indian subcontinent](/Indian_subcontinent), under the rule of the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire)'s sixth emperor, [Aurangzeb](/Aurangzeb), saw a period where governance was guided by [Sharia](/Sharia) law and [Islamic economics](/Islamic_economics). This economic framework, combined with effective administration, propelled India to become the world's largest economy, remarkably accounting for an estimated 25% of global GDP during this time.

