### Great Divergence

The "Great Divergence" stands as a stark historical inflection point, a period that saw European colonial powers systematically and militarily overpower established Oriental powers. This shift began with wealthy polities such as the [Bengal Subah](/Bengal_Subah) within the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) and [Tipu Sultan](/Tipu_Sultan)'s formidable [Kingdom of Mysore](/Kingdom_of_Mysore), extended to the enduring [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire), and encompassed numerous smaller states scattered across the pre-modern [Greater Middle East](/Greater_Middle_East). This decisive military superiority heralded the onset of the era known as '[colonialism](/Colonialism)'. As the astute [Ibrahim Muteferrika](/Ibrahim_Muteferrika) observed in his *Rational basis for the Politics of Nations* (1731), the reason for the Christian nations' newfound dominance, despite their historical weakness relative to Muslim nations, was quite simple: "Because they have laws and rules invented by reason." A rather inconvenient truth, if you ask me.

