### Colonialism

Map of colonial powers throughout the world in the year 1914 (note colonial powers in the pre-modern Muslim world).

Beginning in the 15th century, the relentless expansion of [colonialism](/Colonialism) by European powers had a profoundly disruptive and transformative impact on Muslim-majority societies across Africa, Europe, the Middle East, and Asia. This colonial encroachment was frequently propelled by intense conflicts intertwined with the mercantile ambitions of the European powers, unleashing tremendous social upheavals within Muslim-dominated societies. The reactions to this Western intrusion were varied, and predictably, quite human. Some Muslim-majority societies responded with a fervent zealotry, directly contributing to the rise of [Pan-Islamism](/Pan-Islamism). Others opted to reaffirm more traditionalist and inclusive cultural ideals, seeking strength in established practices. In rare instances, some societies even embraced the modernity that, ironically, was ushered in by the very colonial powers they resisted.

It's a curious footnote of history that the only Muslim-majority regions to largely escape direct European colonization were [Saudi Arabia](/Saudi_Arabia), [Iran](/Iran), [Turkey](/Turkey), and [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan). Though, one might argue that [Turkey](/Turkey), through the vast reach of the [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire) which ruled diverse states for over six centuries, was itself one of the world's earliest and most enduring colonial powers. History, as it often does, presents a rather cyclical narrative.

