### Postcolonial era

The 20th century witnessed the inexorable decline of European colonial domination, giving way to the formation of numerous independent nation-states, many of which harbored significant Muslim populations. These emerging states, in their efforts to forge new identities and systems, drew upon Islamic traditions to varying degrees and in diverse ways, shaping their legal, educational, and economic frameworks. As early as 1912, *The Times* had already begun to document the emergence of the "Muslim world" as a distinct concept, particularly when describing [Pan-Islamism](/Pan-Islamism). They characterized it as a movement possessing considerable power, importance, and an unexpected cohesion, apparently having its genesis in Paris, a city where Turks, Arabs, and Persians found common ground. The article, ever the keen observer, delved into the political standing of the Amir, the far-reaching consequences of the [Tripoli Campaign](/Italo-Turkish_War), the intricate web of [Anglo-Russian actions in Persia](/Persian_Constitutional_Revolution), and the persistent "Afghan Ambitions."

A particularly seismic shift within the Muslim world was the dramatic [defeat and subsequent dissolution of the Ottoman Empire](/Dissolution_of_the_Ottoman_Empire) between 1908 and 1922. A pivotal figure in this epochal transformation was the Ottoman officer and visionary [Turkish revolutionary](/Turkish_National_Movement) statesman, [Mustafa Kemal Atatürk](/Mustafa_Kemal_Atat%C3%BCrk). He played an instrumental role in bringing about the empire's end and replacing it with the [Republic of Turkey](/Republic_of_Turkey), a [modern](/Modernity), [secular democracy](/Secular_democracy). This radical overhaul included the [abolition of the Ottoman sultanate](/Abolition_of_the_Ottoman_sultanate) and, crucially, the formal [separation of religion from the state](/Separation_of_church_and_state) with the [abolition of the Caliphate](/Abolition_of_the_Caliphate) in 1924. The [secular values](/Secularism_in_Turkey) championed by [Kemalism](/Kemalism) in Turkey have, perhaps inevitably, often been interpreted as a direct consequence of Western influence.

Moving into the 21st century, the tragic [September 11 attacks](/September_11_attacks) in 2001, orchestrated by the [Wahhabi](/Wahhabism) [Islamist](/Islamism) [terrorist group](/Islamic_terrorism) [Al-Qaeda](/Al-Qaeda) against the United States, prompted scholars to re-evaluate how Muslim experiences were understood through the lens of secular [Enlightenment](/Western_world) principles. [Muhammad Atta](/Muhammad_Atta), one of the infamous [11 September hijackers](/Hijackers_in_the_September_11_attacks), was reportedly heard quoting from the [Quran](/Quran) to quell his fears: "Fight them, and God will chastise them at your hands/And degrade them, and He will help you/Against them, and bring healing to the breasts of a people who believe." This invocation, referencing the *ummah* (the community of Muslim believers) and drawing upon the potent imagery of early Islamic warriors who guided the faithful out of the darkness of *[jahiliyyah](/Jahiliyyah)*, underscored a profound ideological chasm.

For figures like [Sayyid Qutb](/Sayyid_Qutb), a towering ideologue of modern Islamism, [Islam](/Islam) itself represented "a complete divorce from *jahiliyyah*." He famously lamented that American churches functioned as social hubs, "very hard [to] distinguish from places of fun and amusement," viewing Western society as the epitome of modern *jahiliyyah*. Qutb envisioned a "Muslim world" and its "social order" as a beacon, which, when presented to the West as the authentic outcome of Islamic teachings, would impress "by the beauty and charm of true Islamic ideology." He vociferously argued that the values of the Enlightenment and its scientific precursor, the [Scientific Revolution](/Scientific_Revolution), fundamentally "denies or suspends God's sovereignty on earth." Consequently, he advocated for strengthening "Islamic character" as an essential step "to abolish the negative influences of *jahili* life." A clear call to ideological arms, if ever there was one.

## Islam by country

