* Further information: [Political aspects of Islam](/Political_aspects_of_Islam) and [Islam and secularism](/Islam_and_secularism)

As the Muslim world inevitably collided with [secular](/Secularism) ideals, societies responded with a predictable spectrum of reactions. Some Muslim-majority countries have, against some expectations, firmly embraced secularism. [Azerbaijan](/Azerbaijan), for instance, holds the distinction of becoming the first secular republic in the Muslim world, albeit briefly, between 1918 and 1920, before its absorption into the Soviet Union. [Turkey](/Turkey) has, famously, been governed as a [secular state](/Secular_state) since the sweeping reforms initiated by [Mustafa Kemal Atatürk](/Mustafa_Kemal_Atat%C3%BCrk). Conversely, the 1979 [Iranian Revolution](/Iranian_Revolution) dramatically overturned a monarchical, semi-secular regime, replacing it with an [Islamic republic](/Islamic_republic) under the uncompromising leadership of the [Ayatollah](/Ayatollah), [Ruhollah Khomeini](/Ruhollah_Khomeini). A stark reminder that history rarely moves in a straight line.

Many countries, while not fully embracing an Islamic state model, have nevertheless declared Islam as their official state religion. In these nations, the legal framework often retains a largely secular character, with [Sharia](/Sharia) law typically confined to matters of personal status, such as inheritance and marriage. The implementation of Islamic law, or *sharia* in Arabic, itself manifests in a variety of forms, guided by different [schools of jurisprudence](/Madh%27hab). The [Amman Message](/Amman_Message), a significant declaration endorsed in 2005 by prominent Islamic scholars worldwide, formally recognized four [Sunni](/Sunni_Islam) schools ([Hanafi](/Hanafi), [Maliki](/Maliki), [Shafi'i](/Shafi%27i), [Hanbali](/Hanbali)), two [Shia](/Shia_Islam) schools ([Ja'fari](/Ja%27fari_jurisprudence), [Zaidi](/Zaidiyyah)), the [Ibadi](/Ibadi) school, and the [Zahiri](/Zahiri) school. This acknowledgment highlights the inherent diversity within Islamic legal thought, a complexity often overlooked by outsiders.

