## Politics

* Further information: [Islamic revival](/Islamic_revival) and [Liberalism and progressivism within Islam](/Liberalism_and_progressivism_within_Islam)

[Benazir Bhutto](/Benazir_Bhutto), the former [prime minister of Pakistan](/Prime_minister_of_Pakistan) became the first woman elected to lead a Muslim-majority country.

Throughout much of the 20th century, the prominence of Islamic identity and the sway of Islam over political discourse arguably waxed and waned. However, in the early 21st century, these aspects have seen a notable resurgence. The ever-increasing interest of the Western world in Islamic regions, the proliferation of international conflicts, and the relentless march of [globalization](/Globalization) have collectively reshaped the influence of Islam on the global stage in [contemporary history](/Contemporary_history). It seems the world can't quite decide if it wants to leave religion behind or drag it back into the spotlight.

### Islamism

These paragraphs are an excerpt from [Islamism](/Islamism).

[Islamism](/Islamism) encompasses a broad spectrum of [religious](/Religion) and [political](/Politics) ideological movements, all fundamentally united by the conviction that [Islam](/Islam) ought to exert a profound influence over political systems. Its proponents are steadfast in their belief that Islam is inherently political, and moreover, that Islam, as a comprehensive political system, offers a superior alternative to [communism](/Communism), [liberal democracy](/Liberal_democracy), [capitalism](/Capitalism), and other competing ideologies in its capacity to foster a just and flourishing society. The advocates of Islamism, often referred to as "al-Islamiyyun," are typically affiliated with established Islamic institutions or engage in robust social mobilization movements. Their core tenets emphasize the rigorous implementation of [Sharia](/Sharia) law, the pursuit of [pan-Islamic](/Pan-Islamic) political unity, and the ultimate creation of dedicated [Islamic states](/Islamic_state).

In its original conceptualization, Islamism articulated an ideology aimed at revitalizing Islam to reclaim its historical assertiveness and glory. This involved a process of purifying the faith of perceived foreign elements and reasserting its integral role in "social and political as well as personal life." Crucially, it called for "reordering government and society in accordance with laws prescribed by Islam" (i.e., Sharia). According to at least one observer, author [Robin Wright](/Robin_Wright_(author)), Islamist movements have "arguably altered the Middle East more than any trend since the modern states gained independence," effectively redefining "politics and even borders." Another solitary author, [Graham E. Fuller](/Graham_E._Fuller), has posited a broader understanding of Islamism as a form of [identity politics](/Identity_politics), encompassing "support for [Muslim] identity, authenticity, broader regionalism, revivalism, [and] revitalization of the community." A rather expansive definition, one might say.

Central and undeniably prominent figures in 20th-century Islamism include [Rashid Rida](/Rashid_Rida), [Hassan al-Banna](/Hassan_al-Banna) (the founder of the influential [Muslim Brotherhood](/Muslim_Brotherhood)), [Sayyid Qutb](/Sayyid_Qutb), [Abul A'la Maududi](/Abul_A%27la_Maududi), [Ruhollah Khomeini](/Ruhollah_Khomeini) (the architect of the Islamic Republic of Iran), and [Hassan Al-Turabi](/Hassan_Al-Turabi). The [Syrian](/Syrians) [Sunni](/Sunni) [cleric](/Ulama) Muhammad Rashid Riḍā, a fervent opponent of [Westernization](/Westernization), [Zionism](/Zionism), and [nationalism](/Nationalism), passionately advocated for Sunni internationalism through the revolutionary restoration of a [pan-Islamic](/Pan-Islamism) [Caliphate](/Caliphate) to politically unite the fragmented [Muslim world](/Muslim_world). Riḍā was a staunch proponent of Islamic vanguardism, a conviction that the [Muslim community](/Muslim_community) required guidance from a clerical elite ([ulema](/Ulama)) who would steer efforts in religious education and [Islamic revival](/Islamic_revival). Riḍā's distinctive [Salafi](/Salafi_movement)-[Arabist](/Arabist) synthesis and Islamist ideals profoundly influenced his disciples, notably Hasan al-Banna, an [Egyptian](/Egyptians) schoolteacher who went on to establish the [Muslim Brotherhood](/Muslim_Brotherhood) movement, and [Hajji Amin al-Husayni](/Hajj_Amin_al-Husayni), the ardently [anti-Zionist](/Anti-Zionism) [Grand Mufti of Jerusalem](/Grand_Mufti_of_Jerusalem). Both Al-Banna and Maududi championed a "reformist" strategy, advocating for the re-Islamization of society through dedicated [grassroots](/Grassroots) social and political activism. Other Islamists, such as Al-Turabi, favored a more "revolutionary" approach, seeking to [Islamize](/Islamization) society through the direct exercise of state power. Meanwhile, [Sayyid Qutb](/Sayyid_Qutb) envisioned a synthesis of grassroots Islamization with armed revolution. The term "Islamism" itself has been applied to a wide array of entities, encompassing non-state reform movements, political parties, militias, and even revolutionary groups.

Islamists themselves, quite understandably, tend to prefer terms like "Islamic movement" or "Islamic activism" over "Islamism," often bristling at the implication that Islamism is anything other than a natural, renewed, and revived expression of Islam itself. In public and academic discourse, the term "Islamism" has, perhaps inevitably, acquired connotations of violence, extremism, and human rights violations, largely due to its portrayal in Western mass media. This, in turn, has unfortunately contributed to the phenomenon of [Islamophobia](/Islamophobia) and the perpetuation of simplistic stereotypes.

Prominent Islamist groups and political parties across the globe include the formidable [Muslim Brotherhood](/Muslim_Brotherhood), Turkey's ruling [Justice and Development Party](/Justice_and_Development_Party_(Turkey)), the Palestinian organization [Hamas](/Hamas), the Algerian [Movement of Society for Peace](/Movement_of_Society_for_Peace), the Malaysian [National Trust Party](/National_Trust_Party_(Malaysia)), [Jamaat-e-Islami](/Jamaat-e-Islami) in both [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh_Jamaat-e-Islami) and [Pakistan](/Jamaat-e-Islami_(Pakistan)), and Bosnia's [Party of Democratic Action](/Party_of_Democratic_Action). Following the turbulent period of the [Arab Spring](/Arab_Spring), many [post-Islamist](/Post-Islamism) currents became deeply enmeshed in democratic political processes, attempting to navigate the complexities of pluralistic governance. Concurrently, other factions spawned "the most aggressive and ambitious Islamist [militia](/Militia)" to date, namely the [Islamic State](/Islamic_State) of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL). It's crucial to note, however, that ISIL's extreme ideology and brutal tactics have been overwhelmingly rejected as blasphemous by the vast majority of Islamists themselves.

## Demographics

* See also: [Muslim population growth](/Muslim_population_growth)

Currently, over 24.1% of the world's population identifies as Muslim, amounting to an estimated total of approximately 1.9 billion individuals. These [Muslims](/Muslims) are not a monolith; they constitute majorities in 49 countries, converse in hundreds of distinct languages, and hail from an incredibly diverse array of ethnic backgrounds. The sprawling metropolis of [Karachi](/Karachi) in Pakistan, for instance, holds the distinction of having the largest Muslim population of any city in the world. A truly global community, constantly shifting and growing.

## Geography

* Main article: [Islam by country](/Islam_by_country)

[Indonesia](/Indonesia) is currently the most populous Muslim-majority country.

Given the inherent ambiguities surrounding the terms 'Muslim world' and 'Islamic world' – primarily because no country is entirely homogeneously Muslim, and the threshold for a Muslim minority to be deemed 'significant' remains stubbornly undefined – there is, predictably, no universal consensus on how to precisely delineate the Muslim world geographically. The only widely accepted rule of thumb, offering a semblance of order, dictates that countries must possess a Muslim population exceeding 50% for inclusion. A rather arbitrary line in the sand, but one that persists.

In 2010, a significant 73% of the global Muslim population resided in countries where Muslims constituted the majority, while the remaining 27% lived as minorities. [India's Muslim population](/Islam_in_India), standing at 11% of the world's total Muslim faithful, represents the largest Muslim-minority population globally. Jones (2005) proposed defining a "large minority" as falling between 30% and 50% of a country's population. In 2000, this definition encompassed nine countries: [Eritrea](/Eritrea), [Ethiopia](/Ethiopia), [Guinea-Bissau](/Guinea-Bissau), [Ivory Coast](/Ivory_Coast), [Nigeria](/Nigeria), [North Macedonia](/North_Macedonia), and [Tanzania](/Tanzania). By 2024, however, [Nigeria](/Nigeria) has notably transitioned into a Muslim-majority country, demonstrating the dynamic nature of these demographics.

## Religion

### Islam

The two principal denominations within Islam, the Sunni and Shia sects, diverge primarily on the fundamental question of how the life of the *ummah* (the collective community of the faithful) ought to be governed, and, crucially, the precise role and authority of the [Imam](/Imam). Sunnis steadfastly believe that the legitimate political successor to [Muhammad](/Muhammad), in accordance with the [Sunnah](/Sunnah), should be chosen through a process of *[Shura](/Shura)* (consultation), much as occurred at [the Saqifah](/Saqifah) where [Abu Bakr](/Abu_Bakr), Muhammad's father-in-law, was selected. For Sunnis, Abu Bakr was Muhammad's political, but emphatically *not* his religious, successor. Shias, in stark contrast, maintain that Muhammad explicitly designated his son-in-law, [Ali ibn Abi Talib](/Ali_ibn_Abi_Talib), as his true successor, inheriting both political and religious authority. This foundational disagreement has, rather predictably, shaped centuries of Islamic history, theology, and political landscape.

The overwhelming majority of Muslims worldwide, approximately 87 to 90%, identify as Sunni. Shias and various other groups constitute the remainder, accounting for about 10–13% of the total global Muslim population. Countries with particularly high concentrations of Shia populations include: [Iran](/Iran) (89%), [Azerbaijan](/Azerbaijan) (65%), [Iraq](/Iraq) (60%), [Bahrain](/Bahrain) (60%), [Yemen](/Yemen) (35%), [Turkey](/Turkey) (10%), [Lebanon](/Lebanon) (27%), [Syria](/Syria) (13%), [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan) (10%), [Pakistan](/Pakistan) (10%), and [India](/India) (10%).

[Non-denominational Muslims](/Non-denominational_Muslims) actually form a majority of the Muslim population in seven countries (and a significant plurality in three others): [Albania](/Albania) (65%), [Kyrgyzstan](/Kyrgyzstan) (64%), [Kosovo](/Kosovo) (58%), [Indonesia](/Indonesia) (56%), [Mali](/Mali) (55%), [Bosnia and Herzegovina](/Bosnia_and_Herzegovina) (54%), [Uzbekistan](/Uzbekistan) (54%), [Azerbaijan](/Azerbaijan) (45%), [Russia](/Russia) (45%), and [Nigeria](/Nigeria) (42%). These non-denominational communities are predominantly found in [Central Asia](/Central_Asia). [Kazakhstan](/Kazakhstan), notably, boasts the largest number of non-denominational Muslims, who comprise approximately 74% of its entire population. [Southeastern Europe](/Southeastern_Europe) also hosts a considerable number of non-denominational Muslims, suggesting a regional trend towards less rigid sectarian identification.

The lesser-known [Kharijite](/Kharijites) Muslims maintain their own distinct stronghold in the country of [Oman](/Oman), where they account for a significant 75% of the population. A testament to the enduring diversity within the faith.

