### Islamic schools and branches

* Main article: [Islamic schools and branches](/Islamic_schools_and_branches)

[Islamic schools of law](/Madh%27hab) across the Muslim world

The nascent centuries of Islam, in a rather predictable human fashion, gave rise to three major [sects](/Muslim_sects): [Sunnis](/Sunni), [Shi'as](/Shi%27a), and [Kharijites](/Kharijites). Each of these foundational divisions, in turn, developed its own distinct [jurisprudence schools](/Islamic_jurisprudence) (known as *[madhhab](/Madhhab)*), reflecting divergent methodologies and interpretations of [fiqh](/Fiqh) (Islamic jurisprudence). It seems unity is a fleeting concept, even in matters of faith.

The major Sunni *madhhabs* that emerged and persisted are the [Hanafi](/Hanafi), [Maliki](/Maliki), [Shafi'i](/Shafi%27i), and [Hanbali](/Hanbali) schools. These represent the dominant legal traditions within Sunni Islam, each with its own scholars, texts, and interpretative frameworks.

The major [Shi'a](/Shi%27a) branches, meanwhile, are broadly categorized into [Twelver](/Twelver) (Imami), [Ismaili](/Ismaili) (Sevener), and [Zaidi](/Zaidiyyah) (Fiver) Shiism. [Isma'ilism](/Isma%27ilism) itself later underwent further fragmentation, splitting into the [Nizari Ismaili](/Nizari_Ismaili) and [Musta’li Ismaili](/Musta%E2%80%99li_Ismaili) branches. The Musta’li line then further divided into [Hafizi](/Hafizi) and [Taiyabi Ismailis](/Taiyabi_Ismaili). This lineage also notably gave rise to the [Qarmatian](/Qarmatian) movement and the enigmatic [Druze](/Druze) faith, though the Druze, it must be noted, generally do not self-identify as Muslims. Twelver Shiism, for its part, developed the [Ja'fari jurisprudence](/Ja%27fari_jurisprudence), which itself has branches such as [Akhbarism](/Akhbarism) and [Usulism](/Usulism), and has influenced other movements like the [Alawites](/Alawites), [Shaykism](/Shayki), and [Alevism](/Alevism).

Similarly, the [Kharijites](/Kharijites), a group known for their early, strict interpretations, were initially divided into five major branches: [Sufris](/Sufri), [Azariqa](/Azariqa), [Najdat](/Najdat), Adjarites, and [Ibadis](/Ibadis).

Among this bewildering array of branches and sub-branches, only a select few have managed to endure the relentless march of time and theological debate. These include the [Hanafi](/Hanafi), [Maliki](/Maliki), [Shafi'i](/Shafi%27i), [Hanbali](/Hanbali) Sunni schools; the [Imamiyyah](/Imamiyyah)-[Ja'fari](/Ja%27fari_jurisprudence)-[Usuli](/Usuli), [Nizārī Ismā'īlī](/Niz%C4%81r%C4%AB_Ism%C4%81%27%C4%ABl%C4%AB), [Alevi](/Alevi), [Zaydi](/Zaidiyyah), [Ibadi](/Ibadi), [Zahiri](/Zahiri), [Alawite](/Alawite), [Druze](/Druze), and [Taiyabi](/Taiyabi) communities. Furthermore, the modern era has seen the independent emergence of entirely new schools of thought and movements, such as [Quranist Muslims](/Quranist_Muslims) and [Ahmadi Muslims](/Ahmadi_Muslims), demonstrating that the evolution of religious interpretation is a perpetual process.

