### Other religions

It's often forgotten that many Muslim-majority countries are also home to sizeable non-Muslim minorities. These communities include, but are certainly not limited to, [Christians](/Christianity), [Jews](/Judaism), [Hindus](/Hinduism), [Buddhists](/Buddhism), [Baháʼís](/Bah%C3%A1%CA%BC%C3%AD_Faith), [Druzes](/Druze_faith), [Yazidis](/Yazidism), [Mandaeans](/Mandaeism), [Yarsanis](/Yarsanism), and [Zoroastrians](/Zoroastrianism). A testament to the complex, often messy, historical tapestry of human coexistence.

Church and Mosque in [Istanbul](/Istanbul), Turkey.

The Muslim world, perhaps surprisingly to some, harbors some of the globe's most [ancient Christian communities](/Christianity_in_the_Middle_East). It is also the geographical cradle for several of the most historically significant cities in the [Christian world](/Christian_world)—including three of its five great patriarchates: [Alexandria](/Patriarch_of_Alexandria), [Antioch](/Patriarch_of_Antioch), and [Constantinople](/Ecumenical_Patriarchate_of_Constantinople). Scholars and intellectuals widely concur that [Christians have made significant contributions](/Christian_influences_on_the_Islamic_world) to Arab and Islamic civilization since the very inception of [Islam](/Islam). Their impact on the culture of the [Middle East and North Africa](/Middle_East_and_North_Africa) and other regions has been, by all accounts, substantial. The [Pew Research Center](/Pew_Research_Center) estimated in 2010 that over 64 million [Christians](/Christians) resided in countries with Muslim majorities (excluding Nigeria). The Pew Forum's study further indicated that [Indonesia](/Indonesia) (with 21.1 million) possesses the largest Christian population within the Muslim world, followed by [Egypt](/Egypt), [Chad](/Chad), and [Kazakhstan](/Kazakhstan). Conversely, figures from Adly A. Youssef and Martyn Thomas in 2004 suggested a total of around 30 million Christians living in Muslim-majority countries, with Indonesia again leading in numbers, followed by Egypt. [Nigeria](/Nigeria), notably, presents a unique demographic split, being almost evenly divided between Muslims and Christians, with both communities numbering over 80 million individuals.

In 2018, the [Jewish Agency](/Jewish_Agency) calculated that approximately 27,000 [Jews](/Jews) continued to reside in Arab and Muslim countries. [Jewish communities](/Jewish_history) have maintained a presence across the [Middle East](/Middle_East) and [North Africa](/North_Africa) since the very dawn of Islam. Today, however, the number of Jews living in Muslim countries has been [reduced to a small fraction](/Jewish_exodus_from_the_Muslim_world) of their [former sizes](/Historical_Jewish_population_comparisons). The largest remaining communities of [Jews in Muslim countries](/History_of_the_Jews_under_Muslim_rule) are currently found in the non-Arab nations of [Iran](/Iran) (9,500) and [Turkey](/Turkey) (14,500); both, despite their relative size, are considerably smaller than their historical peaks. Among Arab countries, the largest Jewish community now exists in [Palestine](/Palestine) with approximately 250,000 Jews, followed by [Morocco](/Morocco) with about 2,000, and [Tunisia](/Tunisia) with around 1,000. The global population of [Druze](/Druze) is estimated to be between 800,000 and one million, with the vast majority concentrated in the [Levant](/Levant) region, primarily in [Syria](/Syria) and [Lebanon](/Lebanon).

The 2010 Pew Forum study also highlighted significant [Hindu](/Hindu) minorities in [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh) (13.5 million), [Indonesia](/Indonesia) (4 million), [Pakistan](/Pakistan) (3.3 million), and [Malaysia](/Malaysia) (1.7 million). [Malaysia](/Malaysia) (5 million) also boasts the largest [Buddhist](/Buddhist) population within the Muslim world. [Zoroastrians](/Zoroastrianism), for their part, represent the oldest continuously existing religious community in [Iran](/Iran). A truly diverse landscape, defying simplistic narratives.

