## Literacy and education

The state of literacy within the Muslim world, as one might expect from such a vast and diverse region, varies wildly. [Azerbaijan](/Azerbaijan), for instance, consistently ranks among the top nations globally in its Index of Literacy. Several other member states, including [Iran](/Iran), [Kuwait](/Kuwait), [Kazakhstan](/Kazakhstan), [Tajikistan](/Tajikistan), and [Turkmenistan](/Turkmenistan), boast impressive literacy rates exceeding 97%. Conversely, literacy rates plummet to their lowest in regions like [Mali](/Mali), [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan), [Chad](/Chad), and other parts of Africa, highlighting stark disparities. Interestingly, several Muslim-majority countries, such as [Turkey](/Turkey), [Iran](/Iran), and [Egypt](/Egypt), also demonstrate a high rate of citable scientific publications, indicating a robust, if uneven, commitment to academic output.

In 2015, the International Islamic News Agency reported a rather sobering statistic: nearly 37% of the population of the Muslim world was unable to read or write. This figure was based on reports compiled by the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation and the Islamic Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization. In [Egypt](/Egypt), the most populous Muslim-majority Arab country, a curious trend emerges where the youth female literacy rate actually surpasses that of males. While lower literacy rates are more prevalent in South Asian countries like [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan) and [Pakistan](/Pakistan), these figures are, thankfully, rapidly improving. In the Eastern Middle East, [Iran](/Iran) maintains a high level of youth literacy at 98%. However, [Iraq's](/Iraq) youth literacy rate has seen a sharp and unfortunate decline, plummeting from 85% to 57% during the American-led war and subsequent occupation. [Indonesia](/Indonesia), the world's largest Muslim-majority country, stands out with an impressive 99% youth literacy rate.

A 2011 [Pew Research Center](/Pew_Research_Center) study revealed that, at the time, approximately 36% of all [Muslims](/Muslims) had received no formal schooling whatsoever, with only a scant 8% possessing [graduate](/Academic_degree) and post-graduate degrees. The highest average years of schooling among Muslim-majority countries were found in [Uzbekistan](/Uzbekistan) (11.5 years), [Kuwait](/Kuwait) (11.0 years), and [Kazakhstan](/Kazakhstan) (10.7 years). Overall, the average years of schooling in countries where Muslims constitute the majority stood at 6.0 years, noticeably lagging behind the global average of 7.7 years. For the youngest age group surveyed (25–34), young Muslims exhibited the lowest average levels of education among any major religious group, with an average of 6.7 years of schooling, again falling behind the global average of 8.6 years. The study also highlighted a significant degree of [gender inequality](/Gender_inequality) in educational attainment within Muslim communities, with Muslim women averaging 4.9 years of schooling compared to 6.4 years for Muslim men. A stark reminder that progress is rarely uniformly distributed.

