## Refugees

Muslim [Rohingya refugees](/Rohingya_refugees_in_Bangladesh) in [Cox's Bazar](/Cox%27s_Bazar), Bangladesh.

According to the [UNHCR](/UNHCR), by the close of 2010, Muslim-majority countries collectively hosted a staggering 18 million refugees. A rather stark testament to ongoing global instability.

Since then, Muslim-majority nations have continued to absorb refugees displaced by recent conflicts, most notably the devastating [uprising in Syria](/Syrian_Revolution). By July 2013, the UN reported that the number of [Syrian refugees](/Refugees_of_the_Syrian_civil_war) had tragically surpassed 1.8 million, a figure that has only grown since. In Asia, a particularly acute crisis saw an estimated 625,000 refugees from Rakhine, Myanmar, predominantly Muslim Rohingya, cross the border into [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh) since August 2017. The human cost, it seems, remains consistently high.

## Culture

Throughout the relentless march of history, Muslim cultures have, perhaps predictably, exhibited an astonishing diversity across ethnic, linguistic, and regional lines. According to [M. M. Knight](/Michael_Muhammad_Knight), this inherent diversity extends deeply into beliefs, interpretations, and practices, encompassing a vast array of communities and interests. Knight observes that the perception of the Muslim world among non-Muslims is often shaped by introductory literature about Islam, which tends to present a sanitized, scriptural view. This often includes prescriptive texts and abstract historical narratives, filtered through the authors' own perspectives. While many Muslims might concur with such portrayals, Knight argues that they rarely, if ever, accurately reflect Islam as it is genuinely lived "on the ground," within the complex, messy realities of "real human bodies." It seems the gap between ideal and reality is a universal constant.

### Classical culture

