The term "[Islamic Golden Age](/Islamic_Golden_Age)" has, perhaps somewhat romantically, been ascribed to a particular period in history. During this era, [science](/Science_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world), economic development, and cultural works flourished across much of the Muslim-dominated world. This age is traditionally understood to have commenced during the reign of the [Abbasid](/Abbasid_Caliphate) caliph [Harun al-Rashid](/Harun_al-Rashid) (786–809), marked by the inauguration of the legendary [House of Wisdom](/House_of_Wisdom) in [Baghdad](/Baghdad). Here, scholars from diverse corners of the known world converged, driven by an insatiable thirst for knowledge, seeking to translate and meticulously gather all available wisdom into Arabic. The Golden Age is generally considered to have concluded with the calamitous collapse of the Abbasid caliphate, triggered by the relentless [Mongol invasions](/Mongol_invasions_and_conquests) and the devastating [Siege of Baghdad](/Siege_of_Baghdad_(1258)) in 1258. The Abbasids, it is said, were profoundly influenced by Quranic injunctions and [Hadiths](/Hadith) that stressed the paramount value of knowledge, such as the famous dictum: "the ink of a scholar is more holy than the blood of a martyr." During this vibrant period, the major Islamic capital cities—[Baghdad](/Baghdad), [Cairo](/Cairo), and [Córdoba](/C%C3%B3rdoba,_Andalusia)—transformed into preeminent intellectual centers for science, philosophy, medicine, and education. The Muslim world of this era was not a homogenous entity but rather a dynamic confluence of cultures. It skillfully absorbed, synthesized, and significantly advanced the accumulated knowledge from the ancient [Greek](/Ancient_Greece), [Roman](/Ancient_Rome), [Persian](/Persian_Empire), [Chinese](/History_of_China), [Vedic](/Vedic), [Egyptian](/Ancient_Egypt), and [Phoenician](/Phoenicia) civilizations, creating a truly global intellectual melting pot.

### Ceramics

* Further information: [Alchemy in the medieval Islamic world](/Alchemy_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world)

A [Seljuq](/Seljuq_dynasty), [shatranj](/Shatranj) ([chess](/Chess)) set, glazed [fritware](/Fritware), 12th century.

Between the 8th and 18th centuries, the application of [ceramic glaze](/Ceramic_glaze) became a pervasive and distinctive feature in Islamic art, typically manifesting in the form of exquisitely elaborate [pottery](/Pottery). [Tin-opacified glazing](/Tin-glazing) stands out as one of the earliest and most significant technological innovations pioneered by Islamic potters. The earliest examples of these opaque Islamic glazes, often adorned with intricate blue-painted designs, can be traced back to [Basra](/Basra) around the 8th century. Another notable contribution was the development of *[fritware](/Fritware)*, a composite ceramic body, which originated in 9th-century Iraq. Other pivotal centers of innovative ceramic pottery in the Old World included [Fustat](/Fustat) (flourishing from 975 to 1075), [Damascus](/Damascus) (active from 1100 to approximately 1600), and [Tabriz](/Tabriz) (from 1470 to 1550). These hubs of artistic and technological advancement left an enduring legacy on global ceramic traditions.

### Literature

* Main article: [Islamic literature](/Islamic_literature)
* Further information: [Islamic poetry](/Islamic_poetry)

