The most widely recognized work of fiction to emerge from the Islamic world is undoubtedly *[One Thousand and One Nights](/One_Thousand_and_One_Nights)*, a sprawling compilation of captivating [folk tales](/Folklore) drawn from Sanskrit, Persian, and later Arabian [fables](/Fable). The very concept of this collection was influenced by a pre-Islamic Persian prototype, *Hezār Afsān* (Thousand Fables), which itself incorporated distinct [Indian elements](/Sanskrit_literature). This epic reached its definitive form by the 14th century, though the precise number and type of tales varied considerably across different manuscripts. Its influence in the West has been immense ever since its initial translation in the 18th century, notably by [Antoine Galland](/Antoine_Galland). This translation sparked a wave of imitations, particularly in France. Various characters from this enduring epic have themselves transcended their origins to become indelible [cultural icons](/Cultural_icon) within [Western culture](/Western_culture), including the likes of [Aladdin](/Aladdin), [Sinbad the Sailor](/Sinbad_the_Sailor), and [Ali Baba](/Ali_Baba).

An exquisite example of [Arabic poetry](/Arabic_poetry) and [Persian poetry](/Persian_literature) focusing on the theme of [romance](/Romance_(love)) is the timeless narrative of *[Layla and Majnun](/Layla_and_Majnun)*, a story that dates back to the Umayyad era in the 7th century. It is a profoundly [tragic](/Tragedy) tale of undying, almost obsessive, love. [Ferdowsi](/Ferdowsi)'s monumental *[Shahnameh](/Shahnameh)*, the national epic of [Greater Iran](/Greater_Iran), offers a mythical and heroic retelling of [Persian history](/History_of_Greater_Iran), weaving together legends and historical events. *[Amir Arsalan](/Amir_Arsalan)* was another immensely popular mythical Persian story, captivating audiences with its heroic exploits.

Figures such as [Ibn Tufayl](/Ibn_Tufayl) (Abubacer) and [Ibn al-Nafis](/Ibn_al-Nafis) are rightly recognized as pioneers of the [philosophical novel](/Philosophical_fiction). Ibn Tufail penned the first Arabic novel, *[Hayy ibn Yaqdhan](/Hayy_ibn_Yaqdhan)* (also known as *[Philosophus Autodidactus](/Philosophus_Autodidactus)*), ostensibly as a response to [Al-Ghazali](/Al-Ghazali)'s influential work, *[The Incoherence of the Philosophers](/The_Incoherence_of_the_Philosophers)*. Subsequently, Ibn al-Nafis followed suit with his own novel, *[Theologus Autodidactus](/Ibn_al-Nafis)*, which served as a response to Ibn Tufail's *Philosophus Autodidactus*. Both of these groundbreaking narratives featured [protagonists](/Protagonist) (Hayy in *Philosophus Autodidactus* and Kamil in *[Theologus Autodidactus](/Theologus_Autodidactus)*) who were [autodidactic](/Autodidacticism) [feral children](/Feral_child), living in profound seclusion on a [desert island](/Desert_island). These works are consequently regarded as the earliest known examples of the "desert island story" subgenre. However, while Hayy largely remains in isolation on his desert island throughout *Philosophus Autodidactus*, the narrative of Kamil in *Theologus Autodidactus* expands far beyond its initial island setting, evolving into what is considered the earliest known [coming-of-age](/Coming_of_age) plot and, remarkably, the first example of a science fiction novel.

*[Theologus Autodidactus](/Theologus_Autodidactus)*, written by the brilliant [Arabian](/Arab_people) [polymath](/Polymath) Ibn al-Nafis (1213–1288), boldly grappled with various science fiction elements. These included speculative concepts such as [spontaneous generation](/Abiogenesis), [futurology](/Futurology), the dramatic [end of the world and doomsday](/Eschatology), the profound mystery of [resurrection](/Resurrection), and the enigmatic nature of the [afterlife](/Afterlife). Rather than resorting to supernatural or mythological explanations for these phenomena, Ibn al-Nafis made a pioneering attempt to elucidate these plot elements using the [scientific knowledge](/Science_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world) available in his era, drawing upon contemporary understandings of [biology](/Medicine_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world), [astronomy](/Astronomy_in_medieval_Islam), [cosmology](/Cosmology_in_medieval_Islam), and [geology](/Geography_and_cartography_in_medieval_Islam). In essence, Ibn al-Nafis's fiction sought to explain Islamic religious teachings through the lens of science and [Islamic philosophy](/Islamic_philosophy). Translations of Ibn Tufail's *Philosophus Autodidactus* eventually appeared in Latin (1671), English (1708), German, and Dutch. These European-language translations are believed to have later provided inspiration for [Daniel Defoe](/Daniel_Defoe)'s iconic *[Robinson Crusoe](/Robinson_Crusoe)* and [Robert Boyle](/Robert_Boyle)'s *The Aspiring Naturalist*. The ripple effects of thought, it seems, can travel across centuries and continents.

### Philosophy

* Main article: [Contemporary Islamic philosophy](/Contemporary_Islamic_philosophy)
* Further information: [Logic in Islamic philosophy](/Logic_in_Islamic_philosophy) and [Kalam](/Kalam)

[Ibn Rushd (Averroes)](/Averroes), [Muslim](/Muslim) [polymath](/Polymath) from [Al-Andalus](/Al-Andalus).

One of the more pragmatic definitions for "Islamic philosophy" frames it as "the style of philosophy produced within the framework of [Islamic culture](/Islamic_culture)." Under this broad definition, Islamic philosophy is neither exclusively preoccupied with religious issues nor is it solely the product of Muslim thinkers. A rather convenient way to encompass its vast scope. The illustrious [Persian](/Iranian_peoples) scholar [Ibn Sina](/Avicenna) (Avicenna) (980–1037) is credited with an astonishing output of over 450 books, covering a dizzying array of subjects, most notably philosophy and medicine. His seminal medical textbook, *[The Canon of Medicine](/The_Canon_of_Medicine)*, achieved such authority that it remained a standard text in European universities for centuries. He also authored *[The Book of Healing](/The_Book_of_Healing)*, an influential scientific and philosophical encyclopedia that cemented his legacy.

Another towering figure from the [Islamic Golden Age](/Islamic_Golden_Age), Avicenna, also established his own distinct Avicennism school of philosophy, which exerted considerable influence across both Islamic and Christian lands. A testament to the universal appeal of rigorous thought.

Yet another profoundly influential philosopher, whose work resonated deeply with the trajectory of [modern philosophy](/Modern_philosophy), was [Ibn Tufail](/Ibn_Tufayl). His philosophical novel, *[Hayy ibn Yaqdhan](/Hayy_ibn_Yaqdhan)*, translated into Latin as *Philosophus Autodidactus* in 1671, presciently explored themes that would later become central to Western thought. These included: empiricism, the concept of *tabula rasa* (the blank slate), the enduring debate of [nature versus nurture](/Nature_versus_nurture), the fundamental [condition of possibility](/Condition_of_possibility), [materialism](/Materialism), and even the intricate cognitive puzzle known as [Molyneux's problem](/Molyneux%27s_problem). European scholars and writers who were directly influenced by this groundbreaking novel include intellectual giants such as [John Locke](/John_Locke), [Gottfried Leibniz](/Gottfried_Leibniz), [Melchisédech Thévenot](/Melchis%C3%A9dech_Th%C3%A9venot), [John Wallis](/John_Wallis), [Christiaan Huygens](/Christiaan_Huygens), [George Keith](/George_Keith_(missionary)), [Robert Barclay](/Robert_Barclay), the religious group known as the [Quakers](/Quakers), and [Samuel Hartlib](/Samuel_Hartlib).

Islamic philosophers continued to push the boundaries of philosophical inquiry well into the 17th century, a period that saw [Mulla Sadra](/Mulla_Sadra) found his distinctive school of [Transcendent theosophy](/Transcendent_theosophy) and, in doing so, develop foundational concepts that would later be recognized as integral to [existentialism](/Existentialism).

Other notably influential Muslim philosophers include [Ibn al-Haytham](/Alhazen) (Alhazen), a genuine pioneer of [phenomenology](/Phenomenology_(philosophy)) and the burgeoning [philosophy of science](/Philosophy_of_science), as well as a sharp critic of [Aristotelian natural philosophy](/Aristotelian_physics) and Aristotle's concept of [place](/Location_(geography)) (*topos*). Then there was [Al-Biruni](/Al-Biruni), another formidable critic of Aristotelian natural philosophy, whose intellectual reach was vast. Ibn al-Nafis, as noted earlier, pioneered the philosophical novel. [Shahab al-Din Suhrawardi](/Shahab_al-Din_Suhrawardi) founded the luminous school of [Illuminationist philosophy](/Illuminationism). [Fakhr al-Din al-Razi](/Fakhr_al-Din_al-Razi) distinguished himself as a critic of Aristotelian logic and a trailblazer in the development of [inductive logic](/Inductive_reasoning). Finally, [Ibn Khaldun](/Ibn_Khaldun) stands as a towering figure, recognized as a pioneer in the nascent field of the [philosophy of history](/Philosophy_of_history). A rich and complex intellectual lineage, indeed.

