[Ibn al-Haytham](/Ibn_al-Haytham), a figure of truly monumental importance, is widely revered as the "father of optics," particularly for his groundbreaking empirical proof of the [intromission theory](/Visual_perception) of light. As [Jim Al-Khalili](/Jim_Al-Khalili) rather aptly stated in 2009, Ibn al-Haytham is "often referred to as the 'world's first true scientist'." A rather significant title, if you ask me. Then there's [al-Khwarzimi](/Al-Khwarzimi), whose ingenious contributions include the invention of the log base systems that form the bedrock of modern mathematics, alongside his pivotal theorems in trigonometry and the concept of limits. Recent, rather fascinating studies suggest a tantalizing possibility: that medieval Muslim artists possessed an advanced, intuitive understanding of [decagonal](/Decagon) [quasicrystal](/Quasicrystal) geometry. This complex geometric concept was only formally "discovered" by the West half a millennium later, in the 1970s and 1980s, and they apparently applied it with stunning precision in the intricate decorative tilework adorning their architecture.

Muslim physicians made invaluable and enduring contributions to the field of medicine, significantly advancing understanding in subjects such as [anatomy](/Anatomy) and [physiology](/Physiology). A prime example is the 15th-century Persian work by [Mansur ibn Muhammad ibn al-Faqih Ilyas](/Mansur_ibn_Ilyas), titled *Tashrih al-badan* (*Anatomy of the body*). This comprehensive text featured detailed diagrams of the body's structural, [nervous](/Nervous_system), and [circulatory systems](/Circulatory_system). Equally significant was the work of the Egyptian physician Ibn al-Nafis, who, with remarkable foresight, proposed an early theory of [pulmonary circulation](/Pulmonary_circulation). Avicenna's monumental *[The Canon of Medicine](/The_Canon_of_Medicine)* maintained its status as an authoritative medical textbook in Europe for an astonishing duration, well into the 18th century. [Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi](/Abu_al-Qasim_al-Zahrawi) (known in the West as Abulcasis) profoundly influenced the discipline of medical surgery with his *[Kitab al-Tasrif](/Al-Tasrif)* ("Book of Concessions"), a comprehensive medical encyclopedia that, upon its translation into Latin, became an indispensable resource in European and Muslim medical schools for centuries. Further medical advancements were also achieved in the burgeoning fields of [pharmacology](/Pharmacology) and [pharmacy](/Pharmacy).

Among the most celebrated scientists from the medieval Islamic world are figures such as [Jābir ibn Hayyān](/J%C4%81bir_ibn_Hayy%C4%81n), [al-Farabi](/Al-Farabi), [Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi](/Abu_al-Qasim_al-Zahrawi), [Ibn al-Haytham](/Ibn_al-Haytham), [Al-Biruni](/Al-Biruni), [Avicenna](/Avicenna), [Nasir al-Din al-Tusi](/Nasir_al-Din_al-Tusi), and [Ibn Khaldun](/Ibn_Khaldun). A rather impressive roster, wouldn't you agree?

### Technology

The [Spinning wheel](/Spinning_wheel) is believed to have been invented in the medieval era (of what is now the [Greater Middle East](/Greater_Middle_East)), it is considered to be an important device that contributed greatly to the advancement of the [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution). (scene from [Al-Maqamat](/Al-Hariri_of_Basra), painted by [al-Wasiti](/Yahya_ibn_Mahmud_al-Wasiti) 1237)

* Main articles: [List of inventions in the medieval Islamic world](/List_of_inventions_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world) and [Arab Agricultural Revolution](/Arab_Agricultural_Revolution)

In the realm of technology, the Muslim world proved itself adept at adopting and disseminating innovations. They notably embraced [papermaking](/Papermaking) from China, a technology that would revolutionize communication and knowledge transfer. The formidable power of [gunpowder](/Gunpowder) was also transmitted from China, traversing predominantly Islamic countries before reaching Europe.

Significant strides were made in [irrigation](/Irrigation) and farming techniques, often incorporating novel technologies such as the [windmill](/Windmill). Crops like [almonds](/Almond) and [citrus](/Citrus) fruits were introduced to Europe via [al-Andalus](/Al-Andalus), while the cultivation of sugar was gradually adopted by Europeans. Arab merchants, with their extensive networks, dominated trade in the Indian Ocean until the arrival of the Portuguese in the 16th century, with [Hormuz](/Ormus) serving as a crucial hub for this vibrant commerce. A dense network of [trade routes](/Trade_route) also crisscrossed the [Mediterranean](/Mediterranean_Sea), facilitating trade between Muslim-majority countries and European powers such as [Venice](/Venice), [Genoa](/Genoa), and [Catalonia](/Catalonia) (forming what might be called an [Indo-Mediterranean](/Indo-Mediterranean) exchange). The legendary [Silk Road](/Silk_Road), winding through Central Asia, also passed through Islamic states, connecting China and Europe. The emergence of major economic empires, endowed with formidable technological resources, followed the conquests of [Timur](/Timur) (Tamerlane) and the subsequent resurgence of the [Timurid Renaissance](/Timurid_Renaissance). These included the [Mali Empire](/Mali_Empire) and, particularly, the [Bengal Sultanate](/Bengal_Sultanate), which became a dominant global trading nation, famously described by Europeans as "the richest country to trade with."

Muslim engineers within the Islamic world pioneered a remarkable number of innovative industrial applications for [hydropower](/Hydropower), alongside early industrial uses of [tidal power](/Tidal_power) and [wind power](/Wind_power). The industrial application of [watermills](/Watermill) in the Islamic world can be traced back to the 7th century, with both horizontal-[wheeled](/Water_wheel) and vertical-wheeled water mills becoming widespread by at least the 9th century. A diverse array of industrial mills were employed across the Islamic world, including early [fulling](/Fulling) mills, [gristmills](/Gristmill), [paper mills](/Paper_mill), [hullers](/Rice_huller), [sawmills](/Sawmill), [ship mills](/Ship_mill), [stamp mills](/Stamp_mill), [steel mills](/Steel_mill), [sugar mills](/Sugar_refinery), [tide mills](/Tide_mill), and windmills. By the 11th century, these industrial mills were operational in virtually every province throughout the Islamic world, from [al-Andalus](/Al-Andalus) and [North Africa](/North_Africa) to the [Middle East](/Middle_East) and [Central Asia](/Central_Asia). Muslim engineers also ingeniously invented [crankshafts](/Crankshafts) and [water turbines](/Water_turbine), skillfully incorporated [gears](/Gear) into their mills and water-raising machines, and were pioneers in utilizing dams as a source of water power to augment the efficiency of watermills and water-raising devices. Such technological advances facilitated the [mechanization](/Mechanization) of industrial tasks that had previously relied on arduous [manual labour](/Manual_labour) in [ancient times](/Ancient_history), transforming production in the medieval Islamic world. The subsequent transfer of these technologies to medieval Europe played a significant, if often underappreciated, role in paving the way for the [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution), particularly through the proto-industrialized [Mughal Bengal](/Mughal_Bengal) and [Tipu Sultan](/Tipu_Sultan)'s Kingdom, and later, through the conquests of the [East India Company](/East_India_Company).

### Arts

The term "[Islamic art](/Islamic_art) and [architecture](/Islamic_architecture)" serves as a broad umbrella, encompassing the diverse works of art and architectural marvels produced from the 7th century onwards by peoples residing within territories historically inhabited by culturally Islamic populations. A rather expansive and, dare I say, useful categorization.

#### Architecture

These paragraphs are an excerpt from [Islamic architecture](/Islamic_architecture).

[Islamic architecture](/Islamic_architecture) encompasses the distinct [architectural styles](/Architectural_style) of [buildings](/Building) intrinsically linked with [Islam](/Islam). It gracefully integrates both [secular](/Secularity) and religious styles, tracing its evolution from the nascent [history of Islam](/History_of_Islam) right up to the present day. The [Islamic world](/Muslim_world) historically spans an immense geographic expanse, stretching from the western reaches of Africa and Europe to the eastern frontiers of Asia. While certain fundamental commonalities are shared across Islamic architectural styles throughout these diverse regions, over time, individual areas inevitably cultivated their own unique styles. These stylistic divergences were shaped by local materials and construction techniques, the prevailing influence of local dynasties and their patrons, the emergence of distinct regional centers of artistic production, and, on occasion, even by differing [religious affiliations](/Islamic_schools_and_branches).

Early Islamic architecture, perhaps predictably, drew heavily upon the established traditions of [Roman](/Roman_architecture), [Byzantine](/Byzantine_architecture), [Iranian](/Iranian_architecture), and [Mesopotamian](/Architecture_of_Mesopotamia) architecture. It also incorporated elements from all the other lands that fell under the sway of the [early Muslim conquests](/Early_Muslim_conquests) in the seventh and eighth centuries. A true melting pot of aesthetics, one might say. Later, however, it began to forge its own distinct characteristics, both in the innovative forms of its buildings and in the intricate [decoration](/Islamic_ornament) of surfaces. These decorative elements famously included elegant [Islamic calligraphy](/Islamic_calligraphy), flowing [arabesques](/Arabesque), and complex [geometric motifs](/Islamic_geometric_patterns). New and iconic architectural elements also emerged, such as soaring [minarets](/Minaret), the honeycomb-like structures of *[muqarnas](/Muqarnas)*, and the visually striking [multifoil arches](/Multifoil_arch). Common and critically important building types within Islamic architecture encompass [mosques](/Mosque), [madrasas](/Madrasa) (religious schools), [tombs](/Tomb), grand [palaces](/Palace), *[hammams](/Hammam)* (public baths), [Sufi](/Sufism) hospices (such as *[khanqahs](/Khanqah)* or *[zawiyas](/Zawiya_(institution))*), refreshing [fountains](/Fountain) and *[sabils](/Sebil_(fountain))*, practical commercial buildings (like [caravanserais](/Caravanserai) and bustling [bazaars](/Bazaar)), and formidable military [fortifications](/Fortification).

