#### Aniconism

* Main article: [Aniconism in Islam](/Aniconism_in_Islam)

In Islam, there is a fundamental belief that no visual images or depictions of [God](/God_in_Islam) should exist. This prohibition stems from the concern that such artistic representations could, rather inconveniently, lead to [idolatry](/Idolatry). Instead, Muslims describe God through the numerous [names and attributes](/Names_of_God_in_Islam) that, according to Islamic tradition, He Himself revealed to His creation. Indeed, all but one [sura](/Sura) of the [Quran](/Quran) commence with the profound phrase, "[In the name of God, the Beneficent, the Merciful](/Basmala)." Similarly, depictions of [Muhammad](/Muhammad) are likewise prohibited. This pervasive [aniconism](/Aniconism) and, at times, [iconoclasm](/Iconoclasm), is not unique to Islam; it can also be found, in varying degrees, within Jewish and certain Christian theological traditions. It seems the human struggle with the sacred and the visual is a recurring theme.

#### Arabesque

* Main article: [Arabesque](/Arabesque)

Islamic art frequently, and rather elegantly, incorporates the use of geometrical floral or vegetal designs arranged in a repeating pattern, famously known as the [arabesque](/Arabesque_(Islamic_art)). Such designs are, by their very nature, highly nonrepresentational. This stylistic choice is deeply rooted in the Islamic prohibition against representational depictions, a stance intended to distinguish it from the practices of [pre-Islamic pagan religions](/Arabian_mythology). Despite this overarching principle, it's worth noting that depictional art *does* exist in some Muslim societies, most notably in the exquisite [miniature](/Persian_miniature) style that gained renown in [Persia](/Achaemenid_Empire) and later under the [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire). These miniatures often featured paintings of people and animals, and even vivid depictions of Quranic stories and traditional Islamic narratives, proving that human creativity finds its way. Another profound reason behind the abstract nature of Islamic art is its symbolic function: to represent the transcendence, indivisible unity, and infinite nature of God—an objective rather beautifully achieved by the intricate arabesque. [Islamic calligraphy](/Islamic_calligraphy), an omnipresent and highly revered decoration in Islamic art, typically expresses itself in the form of Quranic verses. Two of the primary scripts employed are the symbolic [Kufic](/Kufic) and the flowing [Naskh](/Naskh_(script)) scripts, which can be found adorning the majestic walls and domes of mosques, the sides of [minbars](/Minbar), and countless other surfaces.

Distinguishing [motifs](/Motif_(visual_arts)) in Islamic architecture have consistently revolved around ordered repetition, radiating structures, and rhythmic, metric patterns. In this regard, [fractal](/Fractal) geometry has proven to be a key underlying utility, particularly in the design of mosques and palaces. Other recurring features employed as motifs include robust columns, sturdy [piers](/Pier_(architecture)), and graceful arches, all meticulously organized and interwoven with alternating sequences of niches and colonnettes. The role of domes in Islamic architecture has been, quite simply, considerable. Their usage spans centuries, first making a notable appearance in 691 with the construction of the iconic [Dome of the Rock](/Dome_of_the_Rock) mosque, and recurring with breathtaking grandeur even up until the 17th century with the ethereal [Taj Mahal](/Taj_Mahal). Indeed, as late as the 19th century, the aesthetic influence of Islamic domes had been so profound that they were consciously incorporated into European architecture.

