#### Girih

These paragraphs are an excerpt from [Girih](/Girih).

*[Girih](/Girih)* (from the [Persian](/Persian_language): گره, "knot," also sometimes rendered as *gereh*) refers to the intricate decorative [Islamic geometric patterns](/Islamic_geometric_patterns) found in [architecture](/Architecture) and various handicraft objects. These patterns are characterized by angled lines that meticulously form an [interlaced](/Interlace_(art)) [strapwork](/Strapwork) design, a testament to exceptional craftsmanship and mathematical understanding.

The origins of *Girih* decoration are believed to have been inspired by Syrian Roman knotwork patterns, which date back to the second century. However, the sophisticated mathematical underpinnings of *Girih* patterns, meticulously structured around multiple lines of symmetry, represent profound innovations in mathematics that originated within the Islamic world after the ninth century. The earliest known examples of *Girih* date from approximately 1000 CE, and this intricate artform flourished with remarkable vitality until the 15th century. *Girih* patterns could be generated through a variety of methods, including the traditional [straightedge and compass construction](/Straightedge_and_compass_construction), the construction of a grid composed of polygons, and the innovative use of a specialized set of *Girih* tiles, each pre-marked with lines that, when assembled, would form the desired pattern. These patterns could be further elaborated by employing two distinct levels of design, as beautifully exemplified at the 1453 [Darb-e Imam](/Darb-e_Imam) shrine. Square repeating units of established patterns could be readily copied and utilized as [templates](/Stencil), and it is plausible that historical pattern books were specifically intended for this purpose, facilitating the widespread dissemination of these designs.

The 15th-century [Topkapı Scroll](/Topkap%C4%B1_Scroll) offers explicit visual evidence, showcasing *Girih* patterns alongside the precise tilings employed to construct them. While a specific set of tiles, comprising a dart and a kite shape, is known to generate aperiodic [Penrose tilings](/Penrose_tiling), there is, intriguingly, no conclusive evidence that such a set was actually utilized in medieval times. *Girih* patterns have graced an eclectic range of materials, including delicate stone screens, as seen at [Fatehpur Sikri](/Fatehpur_Sikri); intricate plasterwork, adorning [mosques](/Mosque) and [madrasas](/Madrasa) such as the [Hunat Hatun Complex](/Hunat_Hatun_Complex) in [Kayseri](/Kayseri); robust metalwork, exemplified at the [Mosque-Madrassa of Sultan Hassan](/Mosque-Madrassa_of_Sultan_Hassan) in [Cairo](/Cairo); and exquisite wood craftsmanship, notably present at the [Mosque–Cathedral of Córdoba](/Mosque%E2%80%93Cathedral_of_C%C3%B3rdoba).

