#### Islamic calligraphy

These paragraphs are an excerpt from [Islamic calligraphy](/Islamic_calligraphy).

[Islamic calligraphy](/Islamic_calligraphy) represents the refined artistic practice of [penmanship](/Penmanship) and [calligraphy](/Calligraphy), specifically applied to languages that utilize the [Arabic alphabet](/Arabic_alphabet) or the various [alphabets derived from it](/Arabic_script). It is a highly stylized and meticulously structured form of [handwriting](/Handwriting) that adheres to a complex set of artistic conventions, frequently employed for [Islamic religious texts](/List_of_Islamic_texts), [architecture](/Islamic_architecture), and decorative purposes. It encompasses a rich diversity of calligraphic traditions, including [Arabic](/Arabic_calligraphy), [Persian](/Persian_calligraphy), [Ottoman](/Ottoman_Turkish_alphabet), and [Urdu](/Urdu_script) calligraphy. In [Arabic](/Arabic_language), it is known as *khatt Arabi* (خط عربي), a term that literally translates to "line," "design," or "construction."

The trajectory of Islamic calligraphy's development is inextricably linked to the [Qur'an](/Qur%27an). Chapters and verses from the Qur'an serve as a common, indeed almost universal, textual foundation upon which Islamic calligraphy is based. While artistic depictions of people and animals are not explicitly forbidden within the Qur'an itself, Islamic traditions have, for centuries, generally limited figural representation in religious contexts, primarily to avert the potential for [idolatry](/Idolatry). Some scholars propose that the distinctive [Kufic script](/Kufic_script) was developed in the late 7th century in [Kufa](/Kufa), Iraq, from which it derives its name. This early, angular style subsequently evolved into several more elaborate forms, including floral, foliated, plaited or interlaced, bordered, and square Kufic. In the [ancient world](/Ancient_world), however, artists sometimes ingeniously circumvented [aniconic](/Aniconism_in_Islam) prohibitions by crafting intricate calligraphic compositions that, when viewed from a distance, formed recognizable shapes and figures using minuscule script. Calligraphy was held in exceptionally high esteem as an art form, regarded as both an aesthetic and a profound moral pursuit. An ancient Arabic proverb eloquently illustrates this point by emphatically stating that "purity of writing is purity of the soul."

Beyond its religious applications, Islamic calligraphy is extensively utilized in secular art, architectural design, and various decorative contexts. Its pervasive prominence within [Islamic art](/Islamic_art) is not solely a consequence of religious constraints on figurative imagery. Rather, it profoundly reflects the central and revered role of writing and the written word within the broader [Islamic culture](/Islamic_culture). Islamic calligraphy primarily evolved from two major foundational styles: [Kufic](/Kufic) and [Naskh](/Naskh_(script)), which then branched into numerous regional and stylistic variations. In the [modern era](/Modern_era), both Arabic and Persian calligraphy have exerted a notable influence on [modern art](/Modern_art), particularly in the post-colonial Middle East, and have also inspired the dynamic fusion style famously known as [calligraffiti](/Calligraffiti).

