### Calendar

Two distinct calendars, in a testament to varied cultural and practical needs, are in use across the Muslim world. One is the [lunar calendar](/Lunar_calendar), which enjoys widespread adoption among Muslims globally and is commonly known in the West as the "[Islamic calendar](/Islamic_calendar)". The other is a [solar calendar](/Solar_calendar), officially employed in [Iran](/Iran). Both systems measure time within the framework of the [Hijri era](/Hijri_era): the lunar calendar meticulously counts [lunar years](/Lunar_year) (comprising twelve [lunar months](/Lunar_month)), while the solar calendar, as its name suggests, counts [solar years](/Solar_year). A rather pragmatic way to organize the passage of time, each suited to its own purpose.

#### Islamic lunar calendar

These paragraphs are an excerpt from [Islamic calendar](/Islamic_calendar).

The Hijri calendar ([Arabic](/Arabic_language): ٱلتَّقْوِيم ٱلْهِجْرِيّ, [romanized](/Romanization_of_Arabic):&#160; *al-taqwīm al-hijrī*), also known in English as the [Islamic calendar](/Islamic_calendar), is a [lunar calendar](/Lunar_calendar) system. It consists of 12 [lunar months](/Lunar_month), resulting in a year that typically comprises 354 or 355 days. This calendar is of paramount importance for determining the correct dates of [Islamic holidays](/Islamic_holiday) and rituals, such as the [annual fasting](/Ramadan) during the month of Ramadan and the designated season for the [great pilgrimage](/Hajj) to Mecca. In almost all countries where Islam is the predominant religion, the [civil calendar](/Civil_calendar) in daily use is the [Gregorian calendar](/Gregorian_calendar), often with [Syriac month-names](/Assyrian_calendar) employed in the [Levant and Mesopotamia](/Arabic_names_of_calendar_months) (including [Iraq](/Iraq), [Syria](/Syria), [Jordan](/Jordan), [Lebanon](/Lebanon), and [Palestine](/Palestine)). However, the religious calendar remains the Hijri one, maintaining its spiritual and cultural significance.

This calendar enumerates the [Hijri era](/Hijri_era), the epoch of which was formally established as the [Islamic New Year](/Islamic_New_Year) in 622 [CE](/Common_Era). During that pivotal year, [Muhammad](/Muhammad) and his devoted followers undertook their momentous migration from [Mecca](/Mecca) to [Medina](/Medina), an event profoundly commemorated as the [Hijrah](/Hijrah). In the Western world, dates within this era are commonly denoted by the abbreviation AH (from [Latin](/Latin_language): *Anno Hegirae*, [lit.](/Literal_translation)&#8201; 'In the year of the Hijrah'). In Muslim countries, it is also frequently abbreviated as H, derived from its Arabic form (*سَنَة هِجْرِيَّة*). Years preceding the Hijra are designated as BH ("Before the Hijra") in English.

As of 26 June 2025 CE, the current Islamic year is 1447&#160;AH. In the [Gregorian calendar](/Gregorian_calendar) reckoning, 1447&#160;AH is set to run from 26&#160;June&#160;2025 to approximately 15&#160;June&#160;2026, though the exact dates can, rather inconveniently, depend on the specific variant of the Islamic calendar being followed.

#### Solar Hijri calendar

These paragraphs are an excerpt from [Solar Hijri calendar](/Solar_Hijri_calendar).

The [Solar Hijri calendar](/Solar_Hijri_calendar) is, rather uniquely, the official calendar of [Iran](/Iran). It functions as a [solar calendar](/Solar_calendar), meticulously structured around the Earth's orbital journey around the Sun. Each year in this system commences precisely on the day of the [March equinox](/March_equinox) and comprises either 365 or 366 days. It is sometimes also referred to as the Shamsi calendar, Khorshidi calendar, or simply the Persian calendar, and represents the most recent iteration of the various [Iranian calendars](/Iranian_calendars). Its abbreviation is typically SH, HS, AP, or, on occasion, AHSh, distinguishing it from the [lunar Hijri calendar](/Islamic_calendar) (more commonly known in the West as the 'Islamic calendar'), which is usually abbreviated as AH.

The [epoch](/Epoch) (the very first day) of the Solar Hijri calendar was established as the spring equinox, specifically March 19, 622 [CE](/Common_era). This calendar is designated as a "Hijri calendar" because that particular year marks the time when [Muhammad](/Muhammad) is believed to have embarked on his pivotal journey from [Mecca](/Mecca) to [Medina](/Medina), an event universally referred to as the [Hijrah](/Hijrah).

Because this calendar relies on precise astronomical observations and complex calculations to determine the [vernal equinox](/March_equinox), it theoretically possesses no inherent error in its alignment with the true vernal equinox year. According to Iranian studies, it predates the lunar Hijri calendar used by the majority of [Muslims](/Muslims) (which, as we know, is referred to in the West as the [Islamic calendar](/Islamic_calendar)); though both calendars count their years starting from the year of the Hijrah. A key distinction is that the solar Hijri calendar utilizes [solar years](/Solar_year) and is calculated based on the "year of the Hijrah," whereas the lunar Hijri calendar is founded upon [lunar months](/Lunar_month) and dates from the presumed actual "day of the Hijrah." The slight difference in starting point, it seems, is enough to create two distinct systems.

Each of the twelve months within the solar Hijri calendar corresponds with a particular [zodiac sign](/Zodiac_sign). Historically, in Iran before 1925, and in [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan) before 2023, the names of these zodiacal signs were directly used for the months. Elsewhere, the month names often align with those found in the [Zoroastrian calendar](/Zoroastrian_calendar). The first six months consist of 31 days, the subsequent five months have 30 days, and the final month contains 29 days in common years, extending to 30 days in [leap years](/Leap_year).

The ancient Iranian New Year's Day, universally known as [Nowruz](/Nowruz), unfailingly coincides with the March equinox. Nowruz is a widely celebrated festival, observed by communities across a vast geographical expanse, stretching from the [Balkans](/Balkans) to [Central Asia](/Central_Asia). Currently, the Solar Hijri calendar holds official status only in Iran. Notably, since 1 Muharam 1444 [AH](/Anno_Hegirae) (30 July 2022 [CE](/Common_Era)), this calendar is no longer used by the government of [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan), which has switched back to the Lunar Hijri calendar. Change, it seems, is the only constant.

### Women

* See also: [Women in Islam](/Women_in_Islam) and [Musawah](/Musawah)

According to Riada Asimovic Akyol, the experiences of Muslim women are, quite naturally, incredibly diverse, shaped by a complex interplay of geographical location and personal circumstances, such as family upbringing, social class, and educational opportunities. Akyol points out that, rather inconveniently, the nuanced distinctions between culture and religion are frequently overlooked by community and state leaders in many Muslim-majority countries. The core issue in the Muslim world concerning gender dynamics, she argues, lies in the fact that religious texts, largely constructed within profoundly patriarchal environments and often rooted in biological [essentialism](/Essentialism), continue to hold immense value within Islam. Consequently, views that emphasize men's inherent superiority and advocate for unequal [gender roles](/Gender_roles_in_Islam) remain widespread among many conservative Muslims, both men and women. Orthodox Muslims often sincerely believe that the rights and responsibilities assigned to women in Islam are distinct from those of men, and are, moreover, sacrosanct, being divinely ordained. [Asma Barlas](/Asma_Barlas) contends that patriarchal behavior among Muslims is fundamentally based on an ideology that conflates sexual and biological differences with rigid gender dualisms and inherent inequality. In response, [modernist discourse](/Islamic_Modernism) from [liberal progressive movements](/Liberalism_and_progressivism_within_Islam), such as [Islamic feminism](/Islamic_feminism), has been actively engaged in re-examining the [hermeneutics of feminism in Islam](/Hermeneutics_of_feminism_in_Islam), striving to interpret religious texts in ways that uphold respect for Muslim women's lives and their fundamental rights. Riada Asimovic Akyol further asserts that achieving genuine equality for Muslim women necessitates a rigorous process of self-criticism within these communities. Change, it seems, must often come from within.

